# Sahil Bloom
## Post 1 (2026)

Nobody talks about reliability.

(It might be the most important skill you can build.)

You can get pretty damn far in life by just being someone people can count on to show up and do the work.

Not the smartest person in the room. 
Not the most connected. 
Not the most talented.

Just reliable.

Stop overcomplicating success.

Show up, do the work, repeat.

## Post 2 (2026)

In 1888, a man read his own obituary.

(He was still alive.)

A French newspaper accidentally published Alfred Nobel's death notice. 

The headline called him a merchant of destruction.

Nobel got something almost nobody gets: a preview of his legacy while he still had time to change it.

He rewrote his will. He gave away 94% of everything he had.

The Nobel Prize was born.

You don't need a newspaper to print your obituary.

You just need to ask yourself one question:

"If I were on my deathbed today, what would I regret?"

I did this exercise. I call it the Deathbed Regret List.

I wrote down 9 things I know I'd regret if I let them slip away:

1. Leaving my family without financial security.

2. Missing my son's Magic Years.

3. Not spending enough time with my parents.

4. Not having the courage to take the leap.

5. Not taking on challenging quests.

6. Allowing meaningful relationships to atrophy.

7. Letting my body and mind deteriorate.

8. Allowing technology to destroy my presence.

9. Losing sight of the beauty of enough.

Jeff Bezos used a version of this when he left his hedge fund to start Amazon.

He projected himself forward, looked back, and asked if he'd regret not trying.

The answer was obvious.

You probably won't get to read your own obituary.

But you can do this exercise today.

Project yourself to the end. Look back.

What would you regret?

Then snap back to now and feel the gratitude that comes from knowing you still have time.

One action at a time.

